edu.rit.util

Class Set<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.rit.util.Set<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - Element data type.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Streamable

    public class Set<E>
extends Object
implements Streamable
    Class Set provides a set of elements. The element must be an object suitable for use in a hashed data structure; that is, the element class must define the equals() and hashCode() methods properly. Elements must not be null. Once an element is stored in a set, the state of the element must not be altered.

    The set calls the protected copyElement() method to make a copy of an element being added to the set. The default is to copy just the element reference. This behavior can be changed by overriding the copyElement() method in a subclass of class Set.

    The set uses the protected same() and hashOf() methods when searching for an element. The default is to use the element class's equals() and hashCode() methods. This behavior can be changed by overriding the same() and hashOf() methods in a subclass of class Set.

    Class Set is streamable. For object streaming to work properly, the element class must be streamable or serializable.

    Note: Class Set is not multiple thread safe.

        public <R> R forEachItemDo(ActionResult<E,R> action)
        Perform the given action on each element in this set and return a result. For each element in this set in an unspecified order, the given action's run() method is called, passing in the element. The state of the element must not be altered.       • removeEachItemIf

        public void removeEachItemIf(Predicate<E> predicate)
        Evaluate the given predicate on, and possibly remove, each element in this set. For each element in this set in an unspecified order, the given predicate's test() method is called, passing in the element. The state of the element must not be altered. If the test() method returns true, the element is removed from this set.

        Warning: If the predicate adds elements to or removes elements from the set, other than by returning true, the removeEachItemIf() method's behavior is not specified.

        Parameters:
        predicate - Predicate.

      • copyElement

        protected E copyElement(E elem)
        Copy the given element. The copyElement() method in class Set merely returns the elem reference; this makes a shallow copy. A subclass of class Set can override the copyElement() method to return something else. Possibilities include:

        • Return a clone of the element, which makes a deep copy.

        • Return an instance of a subclass of the element's class, in which the writeOut() and readIn() methods have been overridden to implement different streaming behavior.
        Parameters:
        elem - Set element to copy.
        Returns:
        Copy of elem.

      • same

        protected boolean same(E elem1,
           E elem2)
        Determine if the given elements are the same. The same() method in class Set returns elem1.equals(elem2). A subclass of class Set can override the same() method to use a different criterion for whether the given elements are the same.

        If the same() method says that two elements are the same, then the hashOf() method must return the same hash value for both elements.

        Parameters:
        elem1 - First element; an element in this set.
        elem2 - Second element; an element that might or might not be in this set.

      • hashOf

        protected int hashOf(E elem)
        Returns a hash value for the given element. The hashOf() method in class Set returns elem.hashCode(). A subclass of class Set can override the hashOf() method to calculate the hash value differently.

        If the same() method says that two elements are the same, then the hashOf() method must return the same hash value for both elements.

        Parameters:
        elem - Element.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - (unchecked exception) Thrown if elem is null.
